"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683435","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Northern Ireland Office has not employed any former prisoners in any of the last five years.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-02-08T16:04:47.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683435/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683435/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683435/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-02-02","Northern Ireland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683436","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-09","<p>To comply with the Data Protection Act and safeguard employee personal data, I am not able to provide the information to questions (a), (c), (d) and (e).</p><p> </p><p>The gender of the three most senior officials can be determined from information in the Northern Ireland Office’s Annual Report and accounts for 2015-16:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/nio-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-16" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/nio-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-16</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-02-09T15:34:48.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683436/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683436/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683436/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-02-02","Northern Ireland Office: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683437","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Northern Ireland Office does not have such a policy.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-02-07T11:46:25.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683437/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683437/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-02-02","National Anthems: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what his Department's policy is on ministerial attendance at events at which the national anthem of Ireland is played.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","62844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683438","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office and is included in this reply.</p><p>Due to provisions under the Data Protection Act (1988), we are unable to release information about specific individuals. Aggregate information about the diversity of the workforce in my Department is available at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/cabinet-office/about/equality-and-diversity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/cabinet-office/about/equality-and-diversity</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","62876","2017-02-08T09:18:25.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683438/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683438/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Prime Minister: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of 10 Downing Street.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683439","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>I understand David Cameron met Lord Rothermere socially on the evening of 11 February. The records on Gov.uk now reflect this.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-30T12:12:37.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683439/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683439/answer","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683439/answer/previousversion/34934","Biography information for Ben Gummer","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Viscount Rothermere","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Prime Minister's predecessor met Lord Rothermere in February or March 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","62917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683440","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office and is included in this reply.</p><p>Information about the number of former prisoners employed by my Department in each of the last five years is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","62950","2017-02-08T09:19:34.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683440/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683440/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Prime Minister: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many former prisoners have been employed by 10 Downing Street in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683441","Public Accounts Commission","false","2017-02-16","<p>The National Audit Office is headed by the Comptroller and Auditor General, Sir Amyas Morse, who is an Officer of the House. He is currently supported by a team of four senior staff, although the current Executive Leadership team is undergoing expansion and a number of changes. All of the current senior team are male, four are white British and one of mixed ethnicity, and one has a declared disability. All of the team are university educated. We do not hold information on socio-economic status.</p>","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh",,"2017-02-16T13:39:51.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683441/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683441/answer",,,,,"24","Public Accounts Commission","Public Accounts Commission","2017-02-02","Public Accounts Commission: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chairman of the Public Accounts Commission, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials in the National Audit Office.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683442","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. Details of ethnicity, gender, disability status, educational background and socio-economic status are a matter for the parent employers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-07T12:10:16.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683442/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683442/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-02-02","Scotland Office: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683443","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. Such matters are for the parent Department.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-09T11:06:10.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683443/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683443/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-02-02","Scotland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683444","Speaker's Committee for the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority","false","2017-02-08","<p>IPSA’s Chief Executive, Marcial Boo, is supported by a team of three senior directors (two male and one female).</p><p>Information relating to IPSA’s senior staff is published on IPSA’s website, available at the following address: <a href="https://www.theipsa.org.uk/about-us/who-we-are/ipsas-senior-staff/" target="_blank">https://www.theipsa.org.uk/about-us/who-we-are/ipsas-senior-staff/</a>. Further information is also published annually in IPSA’s annual report and accounts.</p><p>In line with statutory requirements under the Data Protection Act 1998, we do not publish sensitive personal data, which includes information relating to an individual’s ethnicity or disability status. IPSA does not hold information on employees’ educational background or socio-economic status.</p>","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker",,"2017-02-08T14:10:22.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683444/answer","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683444/answer",,,,,"90","Speaker's Committee for the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority","Speaker's Committee for the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority","2017-02-02","Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Broxbourne, representing the Speaker's Committee for the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority, (IPSA) what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials employed by IPSA.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683445","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Electoral Commission’s Executive Team, including the Chief Executive, is made up of five members and an additional Programme Director, of which:</p><p>(a) 6 are White British<br>(b) 4 are female, 2 are male<br>(c) None have declared a disability<br>(d) 3 were educated to graduate level, 3 to postgraduate level.</p><p>The Electoral Commission does not hold information on the socio-economic status of its staff members. Further information about the Executive Team is available on the <a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/our-work/who-we-are/executive-and-management-team" target="_blank">Commission’s website</a>.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2017-02-06T15:45:32.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683445/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683445/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2017-02-02","Electoral Commission: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials employed by the Electoral Commission.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683446","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-10","<p>The department is not able to provide the requested personal information on the basis that individuals could be identified, which would breach section 40(2) of the Data Protection Act, 1998.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-10T11:00:31.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683446/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683446/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","Department for Transport: Senior Civil servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683447","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-10","<p>Train and station operators are required by their operating licence to establish and comply with a Disabled People's Protection Policy (DPPP). This sets out how they facilitate access to their services and is approved and monitored by the Office of Rail and Road (ORR). ORR’s approval is based on compliance with published guidance, which requires operators to describe who they have consulted with; this could include customer panels or advisory groups. In addition, operators are expected to explain in their DPPP how they will work with local authorities to ensure that stations are clearly and consistently signposted.</p><p> </p><p>Operators must also have due regard to the Department for Transport Code of Practice on ‘Design Standards for Accessible Railway Stations’. This code includes requirements relating to signage. As part of the approval process for each operator, ORR consults with the Disabled Persons Transport Advisory Committee (DPTAC), Transport Focus, and London TravelWatch, where appropriate.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-10T13:03:57.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683447/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683447/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","Railways: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what requirements there are for train operating companies to consult with disabled passengers and groups representing disabled people on the provision of signage and information as part of the development of those companies' Disabled People's Protection Policy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683448","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Bus Services Bill includes powers to introduce an Accessible Information Requirement, for local buses throughout Great Britain to provide audible and visible next stop announcements. The impact assessment for these new powers considered a number of options to increase the provision of audio-visual information on buses and is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/561964/bus-services-bill-accessibility-information-requirement-annex-a.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/561964/bus-services-bill-accessibility-information-requirement-annex-a.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-07T14:59:34.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683448/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683448/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","Bus Services: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the options available to increase the provision of audio-visual information on buses.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","62857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683449","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Public Service Vehicles Accessibility Regulations 2000 (PSVAR) have achieved a step-change in the accessibility of local bus services, including for visually impaired people who benefit from the priority seating, colour-contrasting step edges and hand-holds that it requires. Around 94% of buses in England now comply with the requirements of the PSVAR.</p><p> </p><p>The Bus Services Bill, which is currently before Parliament, includes powers to introduce an Accessible Information Requirement, for local buses throughout Great Britain to provide audible and visible next stop announcements.</p><p> </p><p>I am also preparing to launch a consultation on the Accessibility Action Plan (AAP) which is a cross modal plan to build on our social inclusion agenda by reducing barriers to disabled people accessing transport services.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-07T15:02:42.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683449/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683449/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","Bus Services: Visual Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve access to bus services for people who are visually impaired.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","62858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683450","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>As announced in the Roads Investment Strategy, Highways England are delivering a Smart Motorway on the M60 between junction 8 and junction 18, as part of the Manchester Smart Motorway (which also includes M62 Junction 18 to 20). This is currently being built and is due to open for traffic as planned in September 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England are also upgrading the M60 to Smart Motorway between the M60 junction 24 (M67 Denton Interchange) to junction 4 (M56 Kingsway interchange). This is currently in the early stage of its design development and due to open for traffic as planned in 2019-2020.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-07T14:44:23.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683450/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683450/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","M60","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made towards making the M60 a smart motorway; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","62850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683451","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-10","<p>After a provisional offer of employment is made, candidates are asked to disclose unspent convictions and then a criminal record check is undertaken as a part of the Baseline Personnel Security Standard; however, no documentation regarding criminal history is retained by the Department, nor transferred to the employees’ personnel records.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-10T10:57:04.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683451/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683451/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","Department for Transport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683452","Wales Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>None.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-02-08T11:26:43.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683452/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683452/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-02-02","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683453","Wales Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>To comply with the Data Protection Act and safeguard employee personal data, the Wales Office is unable to provide this information. Some anonymised data on the gender makeup of Wales Office senior officials is reported on an annual basis within the department’s annual accounts:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wales-office-annual-report-2015-16-published" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wales-office-annual-report-2015-16-published</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-02-08T11:29:36.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683453/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683453/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-02-02","Wales Office: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683454","Women and Equalities","false","2017-02-09","<p>This is the first ever public consultation on the matter and it is vital that we get the details and content of the consultation right. We intend to issue the consultation in due course.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-09T10:44:37.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683454/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683454/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-02-02","Castes: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, when the Government plans to launch a public consultation on caste and the Equality Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","62869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683455","Women and Equalities","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Government Equalities Office cannot release information on ethnicity, gender or disability status in relation to specific individuals.</p><p> </p><p>The Government Equalities Office does not hold information about the educational background or socio-economic status of its three most senior officials.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-09T16:47:11.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683455/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683455/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-02-02","Government Equalities Office: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of the Government Equalities Office.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683456","Women and Equalities","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-09T16:43:28.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683456/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683456/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-02-02","Government Equalities Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many former prisoners have been employed by the Government Equalities Office in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683457","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Government’s costings of individual tax and welfare spending measures at each Budget and Autumn Statement are subject to detailed scrutiny and challenge by the Office for Budget Responsibility. Details of the costing for the policy can be found in the Summer Budget 2015 publication here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-09T17:28:02.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683457/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683457/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January 2017 to Question 60655, on universal credit and housing benefit, if he will place in the Library the assumptions by which those estimates were calculated.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683458","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>The information you have request is not available.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-09T17:20:37.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683458/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683458/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683459","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Government has committed to reforming housing support for 18 to 21 year olds as stated in the Manifesto and Budget announcements. This policy is about stopping young people slipping straight into a life on benefits and brings parity to a society where an employed young person may not be able to leave the family home whilst an unemployed young person can.</p><p>We are on track to deliver these changes in April 2017.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-09T17:33:17.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683459/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683459/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Universal Credit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his policy is on removing the automatic entitlement to the housing element of universal credit only for 18 to 21 year olds who are out of work.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683460","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department holds information on the number of claimants who have applied for Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit but the Department does not hold any Management Information on claims made by post or during a home visit.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T15:42:29.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683460/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683460/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2017 to Question 62388, on social security benefits, what information his Department holds on the number of claimants who have applied for (a) jobseekers' allowance and (b) universal credit (i) by post and (ii) during a home visit.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","62980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683461","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Secretary of State and Health and Safety Executive (HSE) have not received any representations on assaults on betting shop staff. HSE does not hold information on the proportion of Association of British Bookmakers member betting shops which have been deemed unsafe for single manning, nor has an assessment been made of the safety of lone staff working in betting shops.</p><p> </p><p>HSE provides guidance to help employers ensure a safe working environment for lone workers <a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg73.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg73.pdf</a> and on controlling the risk of violence to staff (<a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/violence/toolkit/index.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/violence/toolkit/index.htm</a>).</p><p> </p><p>All members of the Association of British Bookmakers should meet the requirements set out in the Voluntary Code of Safety and Security National Standards for Bookmakers published by Safe Bet Alliance in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Local Authorities enforce occupational health and safety legislation in betting shops and violence to staff is an issue which may be a focus for inspection where evidence suggests the risks are not being managed properly.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","62811 ; 62830","2017-02-06T16:07:53.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683461/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683461/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Betting Shops: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent representations he has received on assaults on betting shop staff.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","62829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683462","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Secretary of State and Health and Safety Executive (HSE) have not received any representations on assaults on betting shop staff. HSE does not hold information on the proportion of Association of British Bookmakers member betting shops which have been deemed unsafe for single manning, nor has an assessment been made of the safety of lone staff working in betting shops.</p><p> </p><p>HSE provides guidance to help employers ensure a safe working environment for lone workers <a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg73.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg73.pdf</a> and on controlling the risk of violence to staff (<a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/violence/toolkit/index.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/violence/toolkit/index.htm</a>).</p><p> </p><p>All members of the Association of British Bookmakers should meet the requirements set out in the Voluntary Code of Safety and Security National Standards for Bookmakers published by Safe Bet Alliance in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Local Authorities enforce occupational health and safety legislation in betting shops and violence to staff is an issue which may be a focus for inspection where evidence suggests the risks are not being managed properly.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","62811 ; 62829","2017-02-06T16:07:53.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683462/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683462/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Betting Shops: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether an assessment has been made by the Health and Safety Executive of the safety of lone staff working in betting shops; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","62830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683463","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-08","<p>The reciprocal rights and entitlements that will apply following the UK’s exit are subject to the wider negotiation on our future relationship with the EU. We have not yet begun these negotiations, and so it is not possible to set out any positions in advance.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","62778","2017-02-08T15:00:08.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683463/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683463/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Pensioners: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on UK pensioners living elsewhere in the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","62831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683464","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Age UK report concludes that there should be more support to enable older people to continue in employment. Supporting older people to remain in the labour market, and tackling the barriers to them doing so, remains a key priority for Government. In addition to legislative reforms to abolish the default retirement age and extend the right to request flexible working to all employees, we also published a new strategy ‘Fuller Working Lives: A Partnership Approach’ on 2<sup>nd</sup> February. The Strategy is crucially led by employers, but also sets out the case for action by individuals, and the role of Government in supporting them in planning their careers and their approach to retirement. The Strategy and supporting evidence base are available at the attached web address: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-09T17:55:21.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683464/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683464/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the findings of Age UK's report entitled Working Later, Waiting Longer, published in November 2016, what assessment he has made of the merits of reviewing the effect on groups that are most reliant on their state pension of the existing state pension age timetable to April 2028.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","62870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683465","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-08","<p>DWP’s Executive Team is made up of eight members: six men and two women. We would not be able to report on their ethnicity, disability status or educational background as this is classed as sensitive personal data which has legal protection under the Data Protection Act 1998.</p><p>We are unable to report on their socio-economic background as there is currently no commonly agreed definition for socio-economic background across the Civil Service.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-08T14:31:35.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683465/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683465/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683466","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>A widow’s entitlement to State Pension based on her late husband’s National Insurance contributions, and the amount she may receive if entitled, depends on a number of factors. These include whether she reached State Pension age under the old or new State Pension system (and if the former, how much State Pension she is entitled to in her own right); and when her late husband reached or would have reached State Pension age.</p><p> </p><p>If she has remarried prior to State Pension age, she will not be eligible for any State Pension based on her previous husband’s National Insurance contributions as she has ceased to be a widow by the time her entitlement to State Pension begins.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T13:06:06.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683466/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683466/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the pension status is of women who were widowed but later remarried; and how much state pension they are entitled to relative to the level of their late husband's national insurance contributions.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","62911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683467","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>I can confirm that DWP has contracted directly with the Association of British Credit Unions Limited (ABCUL) for the delivery of the Credit Union Expansion Project (CUEP). ABCUL’s subsidiary Cornerstone Mutual Services (CMS) contracts individually with each Credit Union agreeing specific financial terms and incentives. DWP does not hold statistics on funds that have been allocated to each Credit Union as this forms part of the commercial agreement between CMS and the Credit Unions. It should be noted that the bulk of the CUEP funding has been invested in the development of a shared infrastructure for Credit Unions to modernise their business models and become more sustainable.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-02-09T13:18:06.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683467/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683467/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Credit Unions: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which credit unions have received funding under the Credit Union Expansion Project; and how much each such union has received.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","62924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683468","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>State Pension statements explain that they represent an estimate and not a guarantee of an individual’s State Pension. Around 4.6% of customers contact DWP each month querying the amounts shown in their State Pension statement. These are investigated and if appropriate a revised statement is issued or can be viewed online.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-02-07T12:50:37.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683468/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683468/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations he has received on trends in the number of inaccurate state pension forecasts sent to people nearing retirement age; and whether he plans to take steps to assist those affected by errors in such forecasts.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","62909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683469","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>Pension Credit is an income-related benefit for people who have reached the minimum qualifying age and live in Great Britain. It targets help at the poorest pensioners who have been unable to provide for their retirement. It works by topping up someone’s other income to a standard minimum level. The amount of Pension Credit a person gets depends on how much money they have coming in each week and how much capital they hold (e.g. savings and investments).</p><p> </p><p>Where someone has a partner, their claim will be treated as a couple and their income &amp; capital will be added together when their entitlement is calculated. Therefore, where someone who has been widowed becomes a member of a couple, it is the income (which includes any State Pension) and capital of the couple that will be taken into account in the Pension Credit claim.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-02-07T12:56:32.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683469/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683469/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-02","Pension Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a widow who later remarries is eligible to claim pension credit to top up her income; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","62910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683470","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Green Investment Bank (GIB) has provided the following information:</p><p><strong>Number of staff employed as at 31 March each year since the creation of GIB*</strong></p><p>31st March 2013 – 58</p><p>31st March 2014 – 92</p><p>31st March 2015 - 113</p><p>31st March 2016 – 134</p><p>31st January 2017 - 126</p><p> </p><p><strong>Number of employees exiting GIB as at 31 March each year since the creation of GIB** </strong></p><p> </p><p>31st March 2013 – 3</p><p>31st March 2014 - 10</p><p>31st March 2015 – 14</p><p>31st March 2016 – 13</p><p>31st January 2017 – 14</p><p> </p><p>Of the 14 employees who have left in this current financial year, two left in the period from 1 January 2017 to date.</p><p> </p><p>*Headcount numbers reported as per the People section of GIB’s latest annual report.</p><p> </p><p>**The leavers noted are those individuals who were permanent employees and fixed term contract employees who decided leave ahead of the agreed end date noted in their contract. It does not include temporary staff or those individuals who completed a fixed term contract and left on the agreed end date as detailed within their contract.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-07T15:16:39.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683470/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683470/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff (a) were employed by and (b) left the UK Green Investment Bank in each year since its creation; and how many staff have left that bank in 2017 to date.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683471","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>The apprenticeship levy will come into effect in April 2017. By 2019-20, as set out in the OBR forecast, total UK spending is expected to exceed what we currently forecast to raise through the levy. Spending on apprenticeships in England will be £2.45 billion, and the Devolved Administrations will receive £460 million.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-09T16:07:11.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683471/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683471/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-02","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has been raised by the apprenticeship levy since it was established; and how much of that sum has been subsequently re-invested in apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","62927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683472","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-08","<p>Due to the requirements of the Data Protection Act 1998 which protects individuals’ personal information and data, this information is being withheld.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-08T15:26:07.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683472/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683472/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683473","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-10","<p>Green Investment Bank staff at all levels of the organisation have been kept appropriately updated as the sale process has progressed.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-10T14:09:26.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683473/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683473/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what consultation took place with non-management level staff at the Green Investment Bank on its privatisation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683474","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-07","<p>The number of Acas fulltime equivalent staff and payments to them for 2015/16 and 2016/17 are set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No of staff FTE (average)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>783</p></td><td><p>£45,050,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17 (to end February)</p></td><td><p>759</p></td><td><p>£39,350,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-07T16:45:00.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683474/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683474/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","ACAS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much funding has been paid to ACAS; and how many full-time equivalent staff were employed by that organisation in (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17 to date.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","62979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683475","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Government is carefully considering the recommendations of the Competition and Market Authority and will be responding soon.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-08T15:12:50.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683475/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683475/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to respond to the recommendations of the Competition and Market Authority report on the energy sector, published in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","62988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683476","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>All individuals applying for roles at the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy are subject to Disclosure Scotland checks during the application process.</p><p>In line with the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act (1974), Disclosure Scotland checks confirm the unspent convictions of an individual seeking employment at the department but do not disclose this information. Therefore we do not hold information of any spent convictions an employee may have.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-09T15:13:15.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683476/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683476/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683477","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-10","<p>All offers of employment are subject to clearance through the appropriate vetting processes. Following successful clearance and the individual taking up their offer of employment with the department, any history of criminal convictions would not be held on a central personnel record.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-10T10:42:36.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683477/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683477/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-02","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683478","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-10","<p>UK Export Finance consistently makes enquiries on the standing of agents with the relevant UK overseas diplomatic mission as part of its due diligence on applications that it receives. Its due diligence processes are the same whether or not the applicant has requested the use of special handling arrangements.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-10T10:41:02.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683478/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683478/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-02","UK Export Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether UK Export Finance staff ask for advice from diplomatic missions on agents when special handling arrangements apply.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683479","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-10","<p>As the UK leaves the EU, we are looking at all opportunities to strengthen our trading relationships. Ministers and officials in DIT are working with counterparts in a wide range of markets to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade.</p><p>Since the answer of 27 January, the Prime Minister has agreed with President Trump to take forward high-level talks to lay the groundwork for a UK-US trade agreement once we leave the EU, and to identify the practical steps we can take now. The Prime Minister also announced Joint Working Groups with Turkey and Israel to continue to progress our trade and investment relationships at present, and to prepare the ground for our post-Brexit trading arrangements.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-10T10:39:47.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683479/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683479/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-02","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2017 to Question 60711, with which other countries or groups of countries the Government is planning to enter trade negotiations after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","62826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683480","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-10","<p>The Department does not hold information centrally on educational background or socio-economic status of employees. To answer with the ethnicity, gender and disability breakdown of three most senior officials of the Department risks identification and breaching data protection principles.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-10T10:38:52.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683480/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683480/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-02","Department for International Trade: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683481","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>My Rt. Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade has always been clear that he wanted to see a full debate in Parliament on the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) ahead of the vote on the European Parliament, now scheduled for 15 February. Decisions with respect to the timing and form of a debate are for the business managers in the House of Commons. Due to the pressures of the legislative timetable it has not been possible to hold the debate in the main chamber, but the Government was pleased to have had the opportunity to debate this important matter on 6 February and within the appropriate timetable.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:03:55.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683481/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683481/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-02","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, by whom the decision was made to have a European Committee debate on the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement on 6 February 2017 rather than a debate on the floor of the House; when that decision was made; for what reason that decision was made; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","62945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683482","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Home Office lead on UK passport policy. Of course, the Department for Exiting the European Union is working closely with Home Office. Parliament will be informed of any changes to the passport following UK withdrawal from the European Union.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-07T13:15:48.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683482/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683482/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-02","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for the Home Department on the cost of replacing passports to remove reference to the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","62922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683483","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-10","<p>The information requested cannot be released as individuals may be identifiable. The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to the creation of a diverse and inclusive working environment to ensure staff do not face any barriers to success, and all staff feel supported at work. As such, the Department is committed to the steps established in the 2016 Talent Action Plan to help the Civil Service become the most inclusive employer in the UK. The department is also committed to working with a diverse range of external organisations, to ensure our work reflects a broad range of opinions across the UK.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-10T14:26:18.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683483/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683483/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-02","Department for Exiting the European Union: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683484","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-08","<p>There is no precedent for a country triggering Article 50, let alone seeking to reverse such a decision. But as a matter of policy the Government’s view is that once given, our notification will not be withdrawn. A clear majority of the electorate voted to leave the EU and we will respect the will of the British people.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-08T15:04:00.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683484/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683484/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-02","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether the Government has taken legal advice on the possibility of reversing a trigger of Article 50.","false","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","62901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683485","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-10","<p>The Government is currently considering all aspects of its future relationship with the EU, including the precise way in which we will control the movement of EU nationals to Britain after EU exit. We recognise the importance of having access to an affordable, secure and sustainable supply of energy for business and domestic use, as well as continued co-ordination on energy, including for nuclear safety and energy-related research.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-02-10T14:20:54.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683485/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683485/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-02","UK Trade with EU: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of changes to UK rules on movement on the UK's negotiations relating to securing a trade agreement on energy with the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","62825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683486","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-07","<p>This Government is fully committed to the prohibition of torture and inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment. We have been clear that we condemn it and that will not change. <br> <br>The Government has no plans to withdraw from the European Convention on Human Rights. The UK has a long-standing tradition of ensuring our rights and traditional liberties are protected domestically and of fulfilling our international human rights obligations. The decision to leave the European Union does not change that.<strong><br></strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-07T17:10:26.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683486/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683486/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-02","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what his policy is on retaining Article 3 of the European Convention on Human Rights in UK law after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","62845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683487","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-10","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union does not hold this information centrally as a large majority of staff are on loan. This information would be held by the Department issuing the clearance. All Civil Servants employed in this Department are subject to BPSS and security clearance checks. <br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-10T14:31:01.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683487/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683487/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-02","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many former prisoners have been employed by his Department in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683488","Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster","false","2017-02-24","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given by My Rt. Hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet office on 8 February 2017 to PQ62876.</p><p>Please note that the answer to this question is late on account of an administrative error in the Table Office.</p>","Derbyshire Dales","Sir Patrick McLoughlin",,"2017-02-24T10:10:42.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683488/answer","Biography information for Sir Patrick McLoughlin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683488/answer",,,,,"205","Duchy of Lancaster","Duchy of Lancaster","2017-02-02","Duchy of Lancaster: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster, what the (a) ethnicity, (b) gender, (c) disability status, (d) educational background and (e) socio-economic status is of the three most senior officials of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683622","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-14","<p>The government believes that HS2 should be designed to a maximum speed of 360km/h, with a route alignment enabling up to 400km/h in the future. In 2012 HS2 Ltd advised that the cost of building the Phase 1 consulted route at 200km/h would be 9% lower than the cost of a route designed to a maximum speed of 360km/h. An intermediate speed option of 300km/h was considered to test the operating cost and value for money implications of a lower operating speed. This option increased journey times, reducing the forecast benefit-cost ratio of the Scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst a lower operating speed – including 320 km/h - could result in marginally reduced rolling stock capital costs and some reduction to operating costs; these are more than offset by the significant loss in revenue and user benefits.</p><p>It is too early to confirm whether the manufacture or assembly of the trains will take place in the UK. However, when tendering, bidders will be required to make clear how their proposal in respect of designing, building, testing and maintaining the rolling stock will deliver the HS2 Programme’s strategic goals and objectives. These include the development of long term design and manufacturing skills, creation of employment opportunities and investment in workforce education to add value to the UK economy.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-14T11:53:02.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683622/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683622/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 1 February (HL4840), what estimate they have made of the percentage reduction in capital and operating cost of HS2 if the maximum operating speed were 320 kph rather than 360 kph; and whether there is to be a requirement that the manufacture or assembly of the trains will be undertaken in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL5185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683623","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-14","<p>Article 51 of Regulation No 651/2014 is a permissive provision that specifies types of aid that will be deemed compatible with EU state aid rules. The Article itself does not require any action to be taken for it to be introduced in Member States; this is a Regulation and is directly applicable. The decision of whether to grant such aid is one for Member States.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-14T11:50:18.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683623/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683623/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","Transport: Rural Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how Article 51 of Regulation (EU) No 651/2014 concerning social aid for transport for residents of remote regions can be introduced in England; for what purposes; and what aid is already in place.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL5186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683624","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-15","<p>The information requested is not held.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is responsible for protecting the Exchequer from alcohol duty fraud. The majority of this fraud in the UK relates to the diversion of genuine products, without payment of duty. HMRC has a published strategy for dealing with alcohol fraud. This is risk-based and sampling does not form part of this approach.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-15T14:29:41.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683624/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683624/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-02","Wines: Imports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many imported bottles of wine were sampled in each of the last five years, in order to check for fraud and forgery, broken down by samples from (1) EU member states, and (2) the rest of the world.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683625","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-13","<p>Wine sampling is conducted by Her Majesty’s Government on a random and risk-led basis. It therefore remains fully adaptable to respond to actual and perceived risks faced by the wine sector and consumers.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-02-13T14:16:21.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683625/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683625/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-02","Wines: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether sampling of Spanish and French wine has been increased in the light of allegations that cheap Spanish wine is being labelled as French wine.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683626","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-14","<p>The Government is increasing the fixed penalty notice for using a hand held phone when driving from 3 to 6 points and £100 to £200 from 1 March 2017. We plan to evaluate the effectiveness of this action. There are no further measures planned.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-14T11:50:52.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683626/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683626/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-02","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to amend the law to allow the automatic confiscation of a mobile phone that has been used illegally by a driver.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683627","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-09","<p>The United Kingdom meets the Defence Investment Pledge from the NATO summit in Wales, and has committed to do so for the rest of this decade. NATO's ability to deter potential adversaries requires modern capabilities, and these need appropriate funding. Government ministers regularly encourage Allies to fulfil the commitments they have made to spend two per cent of GDP on defence by 2024 (and 20 per cent of that on equipment). Better burden-sharing is an important issue for the new US Administration, and we expect this to be a focus of discussion at the NATO Defence Ministerial Meeting later this month.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL5236","2017-02-09T15:47:47.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683627/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683627/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-02","Defence: Expenditure","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the governments of NATO countries which spend less than two per cent of GDP on defence.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683628","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-15","<p>The most recent figures for UK military personnel based in European NATO countries can be found in the document entitled <em>'Quarterly location statistics: 1 October 2016', </em>which can be found on the gov.uk website at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/location-of-uk-regular-service-and-civilian-personnel-quarterly-statistics-2016</p><p>The following units are based in Germany: HQ British Forces Germany; HQ 20th Armoured Infantry Brigade; The Queen's Royal Hussars; 26 Regiment Royal Artillery; 35 Engineer Regiment; 1st Battalion The Princess of Wales' Royal Regiment; 1 Medical Regiment; 3rd Battalion Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers; Theatre Fleet Support Unit (Germany).</p><p>The UK does not hold information on the personnel and units of the US and Canada based in European NATO countries.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-15T16:07:15.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683628/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683628/answer","20170214 - HL5191 - UK military personnel based in other NATO countries in Europe.xlsx","HL5191 - Quarterly Location Statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683628/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-02","NATO","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the total number of troops and units which the UK, USA and Canada have stationed in other NATO countries in Europe.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL5191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683629","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-14","<p>The Government does not currently intend to review the law.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-14T14:14:11.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683629/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683629/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","Tax Avoidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Young of Cookham on 28 December 2016 (HL4016), and in the light of the LuxLeaks trials in Luxembourg, whether they intend to review their policy of not offering immunity from prosecution to whistle-blowers in so far as it applies to cases where information has been supplied about aggressive tax avoidance schemes that have caused a significant loss to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Lord Harries of Pentregarth",,"Lord Harries of Pentregarth","HL5192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683630","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>As stated in my response of 21 December 2016 (HL4016), the Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998 ensures that workers who raise concerns of wrongdoing to their employer or a relevant external body (by making what is known as a ‘protected disclosure’) and suffer detriment as a result may seek redress through an Employment Tribunal.</p><p>When a finding of unlawful practices has been made against the organisation at a Employment Tribunal, a public body may exclude that organisation from participation in a procurement procedure. This is laid out in the discretionary exclusion grounds of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015. Such a finding has not been made against PwC as a result of the LuxLeaks trials.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-02-20T12:18:29.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683630/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683630/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Tax Avoidance: Luxembourg","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Young of Cookham on 28 December 2016 (HL4016), and in the light of the involvement of PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in the LuxLeaks trials in Luxembourg and the reported pressure placed upon one of the LuxLeaks whistle-blowers to sign a secrecy agreement, whether they intend to desist from conducting any further Government business with PwC.","false","Biography information for Lord Harries of Pentregarth",,"Lord Harries of Pentregarth","HL5193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683631","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-15","<p>The Government believes that profits should be taxed where economic activities are performed. The UK has introduced the OECD model of country-by-country reporting. This will provide a clear overall picture of the global position on profit and tax of multinational groups to tax authorities, enabling them to make more informed assessments of where risks lie.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has set out its objective for a comprehensive and effective model of public country-by-country reporting that is agreed on a multilateral basis, to improve transparency over businesses’ tax affairs and build public trust in the tax system. The UK will continue to work with international partners with a view to delivering on that objective. This includes our continued participation in the discussions on the European Commission’s proposal.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-15T14:28:44.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683631/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683631/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-02","Multinational Companies: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 18 January (HL Deb, col 212), and in the light of paragraph 17(7) of Schedule 19 to the Finance Act 2016 which provides for the Treasury to make regulations requiring group tax strategies to include a country-by-country report, what steps they are taking to ensure that transnational companies are fully transparent about the real centres of their economic activity and reveal any misalignment between that and where such companies declare their profits for tax purposes in their annual accounts.","false","Biography information for Lord Harries of Pentregarth",,"Lord Harries of Pentregarth","HL5194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683632","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-08","<p>The UK Government is committed to withdrawing from the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) and putting in place a new fisheries regime.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will continue to champion sustainable fisheries, including restoring stocks to Maximum Sustainable yield and ending discards, and is committed to cooperating with other countries over the management of shared stocks. We want to use this opportunity to deliver a sustainable fishing industry and marine environment.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-02-08T16:18:31.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683632/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683632/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-02","Common Fisheries Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to leave the Common Fisheries Policy when the UK leaves the EU; and if so, how they will ensure that fish stocks remain sustainable.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL5195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683633","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-08","<p>While the UK remains a member of the EU, we will continue to meet our obligations under EU law. This includes restrictions on the use of neonicotinoids. As part of the preparation for EU exit, we are considering future arrangements for pesticides. Our highest priority will continue to be the protection of people and the environment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government remains of the view that decisions on the use of neonicotinoids and other pesticides should be based on a careful scientific assessment of the risks. Pesticides that carry unacceptable risks to bees, other pollinators and the environment should not be authorised.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-02-08T15:34:35.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683633/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683633/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-02","Neonicotinoids","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to remove the current restrictions on the use of neonicotinoids when the UK leaves the EU; and if so, what is their assessment of the impact this will have on the populations of bees and other pollinators.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL5196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683634","Department of Health","false","2017-02-16","<p>NHS Digital publishes annually the average daily rate of delayed transfers of care from National Health Service hospitals in England per 100,000 local authority population aged 18 years and over. Rates are shown separately for all delays, and for delays attributable to social care, the National Health Service, and jointly to social care and the NHS.</p><p>The most recently published data are for 1 April 2015 to 31 March 2016 and are attached due to the size of the data.</p><p>Information is not collected centrally on the number of successful discharges by council area. In 2015-16, there were 16.5 million finished discharged episodes of NHS commissioned care from hospitals in England.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-16T15:47:03.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683634/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683634/answer","Delayed transfer of care 2015-16 data.xlsx","Delayed transfer of care 2015-16 data","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683634/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-02","Hospital Beds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what analysis they have commissioned to assess the number of delayed transfers of care by council area in the context of population size; and how many successful discharges there have been in each of those areas from hospitals to further NHS or social care services.","true","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL5197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683635","Department for Education","false","2017-02-08","<p>As part of our strategy to increase further the number of pupils being taught in good or outstanding schools since January 2012, we have re-brokered the attached list of 318 academies to new trusts. Re-brokerage can happen for a number of reasons such as a result of intervention action by the Regional School Commissioner, a single academy trust seeking to join or set up a multi academy trust, or a sponsor deciding to hand back an academy because it no longer has the capacity to run it. We are committed to publishing the costs of individual re-brokerages cases on gov.uk in due course.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-08T15:47:39.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683635/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683635/answer","HL5198 attachment.docx","list of 318 academies to new trusts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683635/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-02","Academies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many academies have been transferred from one trust to another, in which years, and what were their names; and what is (1) the total cost, and (2) the individual cost, of those transfers so far.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683636","Department for Education","false","2017-02-10","<p>Private providers of higher education must meet robust financial sustainability standards in order to be designated for student support. Providers that have not been trading for three years must submit a plan to ensure that students can achieve their academic outcomes if they are unable to fully deliver their course.</p><p>In cases of significant financial failure where a private provider goes into administration, the department may grant temporary designation to the new owners to protect the student interest and to allow students to complete their studies.</p><p>The UK quality code for higher education sets out the responsibility of degree awarding bodies when providers delivering their courses become insolvent, cease trading or the agreement is terminated. Degree awarding bodies ensure that adequate contingency plans are in place against these possibilities, but where they occur, a range of solutions may be possible for ensuring that students who wish to complete their course can do so.</p><p>The Higher Education and Research Bill will ensure that in future the Office for Students (OfS) has the necessary powers to require student protection plans are in place for all approved and approved (fee cap) providers, and to intervene if there are signs that quality in any HE institution is failing. The OfS will take a ‘risk based’ approach to student protection, ensuring that the level of protection required in the plan is proportionate to each provider. It is intended that the OfS will monitor the financial health of institutions, alongside other potential ‘triggers’, and will require student protection measures to be implemented whenever there is a risk to student’s continuity of study. We expect these student protection plans to be available to all students, and to set out the protections students can expect if a course closes, or in the rare instance where an institution decides to exit the market.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2017-02-10T14:58:36.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683636/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683636/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-02","Private Education: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what mechanisms are in place to support and safeguard a student if the private college they attend goes into liquidation.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683637","Department for Education","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Government announced a £2.8m investment in tackling homophobic, biphobic and transphobic (HBT) bullying in September 2016. This followed the successful completion of a £2m pilot programme last year. Since we announced this programme, a further £0.2m has been allocated in order to enable more robust evaluation and quality assurance of the programme. This brings the total to £3.0m.</p><p>Six grantee organisations were selected through open competition to deliver innovative schemes to tackle HBT bullying in schools which have no or ineffective measures in place. These were: Barnardo’s, LGBT Consortium, Metro Charity, National Children’s Bureau, Proud Trust and Stonewall. The Government has also contracted with the PSHE Association to quality assure the resources produced as part of the programme and Sheffield Hallam University to assess the impact of the programme. The funding for the programme is split between these organisations.</p><p>Since September, the six grantees have been further developing their implementation plans and they have been registering schools to be part of the programme. The aim is that the grantees will start working with schools during 2017. An action plan for the current programme has not been published and we do not intend to do so. We published the evidence from the pilot programme on GOV.UK in July 2016. A report demonstrating the evidence from, and the impact of, the current programme will be published after this programme concludes in 2019.</p><p>The Government has used a wide variety of evidence to inform its decision to tackle HBT bullying, including external research and the evidence from the 2015-2016 pilot programme. The organisations funded through the programme have been and will continue to be in regular contact with local authorities, academy chains and individual schools as they are recruiting schools.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-09T16:46:36.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683637/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683637/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-02","Schools: Homophobia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Nash on 1 February (HL5039), how far their three-year programme to prevent and address homophobic, biphobic and transphobic bullying in schools has progressed; whether an action plan for the programme has been published; on what basis (1) local authorities, (2) academy chains, and (3) individual schools, have been contacted to seek information about their experience of such bullying; and how the programme funds are being spent.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL5200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683638","Department of Health","false","2017-02-15","<p>At this stage of the application cycle, based on the data the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service published on 2 February, Health Education England is confident that the National Health Service will be able to fill the number of nursing and midwifery places in England.</p><p>The intention of the reforms in England is to boost participation and secure the future supply of home-grown nurses to the NHS. They will also enable universities to create additional nursing, midwifery and allied health professional university training places in this Parliament.</p><p>Students will see an increase in the amount of living cost support they have in hand when studying. We can build on the success of the wider higher education system and support students from all backgrounds pursue their chosen health career, as well as amending access rules for those who already have a degree. More widely, we are focusing on the needs of the profession by continuing to develop options which allow a number of routes into the workforce.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-15T14:13:15.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683638/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683638/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-02","Health Professions: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the reduction in the number of applications by students in England for nursing and midwifery courses at British universities beginning in 2017 compared to courses beginning in 2016 reported by UCAS; and whether, in the light of the smaller reduction in such applications in Scotland and Wales where bursaries are available, they intend to reconsider the decision to abolish NHS bursaries.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL5201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683639","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-16","<p>The UK is a world leader in fusion research and development (R&amp;D) and we have no intention of compromising this following the government’s decision to withdraw from the Euratom Treaty. We fully recognise the importance of international collaboration in fusion research and the UK’s key role in these efforts.</p><p> </p><p>Maintaining and building on our world-leading fusion expertise and securing alternative routes into the international fusion R&amp;D projects such as the Joint European Torus (JET) project at the Culham Centre will be a priority. Government is working closely with the UK Atomic Energy Authority on ways to achieve this.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-16T12:37:03.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683639/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683639/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-02","Nuclear Fusion: Research","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the fusion research programme at the Culham Centre will continue to be funded following the UK's departure from the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone",,"Baroness Featherstone","HL5202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683640","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-14","<p>The table below shows the number of cases subject to suspended committals for non-payment of Council Tax over the last three years by gender. There are a few cases where the gender is not known. Data relating to age is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Male </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Female </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Not Known</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>549</p></td><td><p>482</p></td><td><p>148</p></td><td><p>1,179</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>547</p></td><td><p>402</p></td><td><p>166</p></td><td><p>1,115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 (January -September)</p></td><td><p>313</p></td><td><p>232</p></td><td><p>137</p></td><td><p>682</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>It is possible that one defendant may have more than one case.</p><p> </p><p>Although suspended committals are reported as occurring within a particular year, the non-payment of Council Tax itself may be from a previous year or even a period covering more than one year.</p><p> </p><p>This data is sourced from the HMCTS Libra Management Information System (MIS), and does not form part of the statistics for England and Wales published by the Ministry of Justice, which can be found at: <a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.justice.gov.uk</a>. As such this data set is not subject to the same levels of quality assurance.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-14T16:04:54.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683640/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/683640/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-02","Council Tax: Non-payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people have been subject to suspended committals for non-payment of council tax over the last three years; and what was the breakdown by (1) gender, and (2) age groups.","false","Biography information for Baroness Afshar",,"Baroness Afshar","HL5203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686576","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-14","<p>The Government greatly values the important work that public sector workers do to deliver essential public services. I hold regular bi-laterals with the Chief Secretary to the Treasury. The Summer Budget 2015 confirmed that the Government would fund public sector workforces for an average pay award of 1 per cent for the next four years.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-14T10:16:50.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686576/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686576/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on when the Government plans to end the public sector pay freeze.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","908675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686577","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department. The Civil Service constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government's commitment to leave the EU and get the best deal for the UK. Civil Service HR is working with all departments across the Civil Service to better understand their capacity and capability requirements.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-08T17:51:33.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686577/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686577/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Civil Servants: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he has taken to ensure that the civil service has the number of people it needs in each Department to deal with the implications of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","908674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686578","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department. The Civil Service constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government's commitment to leave the EU and get the best deal for the UK. Civil Service HR is working with all departments across the Civil Service to better understand their capacity and capability requirements.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-08T17:50:55.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686578/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686578/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Civil Servants: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK's decision to leave the EU on the size of the civil service workforce.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","908671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686579","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The UK is recognised as a world leader in transparency and this government is committed to being the most transparent in the world. We publish an unprecedented amount of data about the workings of government and we will continue to do so, both to encourage innovation and transform our public services.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-08T17:51:16.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686579/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/686579/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-02","Government: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his  Department has taken to improve transparency in government.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","908673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682654","Home Office","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Code of Practice for Official Statistics has established common standards to ensure a coherent and trustworthy service to the user of statistics.</p><p><br> Home Office officials are continuing to review and assess information on the number of people claiming asylum where sexual orientation may form the basis of the claim, in order to ensure that any statistics produced meet the principles on both assured methodology and quality (ensuring statistical methods are consistent with scientific principles) and governing user needs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL5159 ; HL5160 ; HL5161","2017-02-09T14:00:46.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682654/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682654/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-01","Asylum: Uganda","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many LGBT asylum seekers from Uganda have been held in UK detention centres in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL5158"
